# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: json-schema
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Data exchange is similar to data integration except that data may be restructured with possible loss of content.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] There may be no way to transform a particular collection based on exchange constraints.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Conversely, there may be multiple ways to transform the data, in which case one option must be identified in order to achieve compatibility between source and target.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] There are two main types of data exchange: broadcast and peer-to-peer (a.k.a. unicast).
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] For broadcast, data is transmitted simultaneously to all consumers.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Just as a conference call, all participants get the same information from the speaker at the same time.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] For peer-to-peer, data is sent to a single receiver, defined by a specific address.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] For example, a letter goes to just one mail box.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] In some domains, a multiple source and target schema (proprietary data formats) may exist.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] An exchange or interchange format is often developed for a single domain, and then necessary routines (mappings) are written to (indirectly) transform/translate each and every source schema to each and every target schema by using the interchange format as an intermediate step.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] That requires less work than writing and debugging the many routines that would be required to directly translate each source schema directly to each target schema.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] A data exchange (a.k.a. interchange) language defines a domain-independent way to represent data.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] These languages have evolved from being markup and display-oriented to support the encoding of metadata that describes the structural attributes of the information.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Practice has shown that certain types of formal languages are better suited for this task than others, since their specification is driven by a formal process instead of particular software implementation.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] For example, XML is a markup language that was designed to enable the creation of dialects (the definition of domain-specific sublanguages).
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] However, it does not contain domain-specific dictionaries or fact types.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Beneficial to a reliable data exchange is the availability of standard dictionaries-taxonomies and tools libraries such as parsers, schema validators, and transformation tools.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] The popularity of XML for data exchange on the World Wide Web has several reasons.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] First of all, it is closely related to the preexisting standards Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), and as such a parser written to support these two languages can be easily extended to support XML as well.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] For example, XHTML has been defined as a format that is formal XML, but understood correctly by most (if not all) HTML parsers.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] YAML was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor with notion similar to reStructuredText and wiki syntax.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] YAML 1.2 also includes a shorthand notion that is compatible with JSON, and as such any JSON document is also valid YAML; this however does not hold the other way.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] REBOL was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] It uses a simple free-form syntax with minimal punctuation and a rich set of data types (such as URL, email, date and time, tuple, string, tag) that respect common standards.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] It is designed to not need any additional meta-language, being designed in a metacircular fashion which is why the parse dialect used for definitions and transformations of REBOL dialects is also itself a dialect of REBOL.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] REBOL was used as a source of inspiration for JSON.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] The dictionary also includes standardized fact types.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] The terms and relation types together can be used to create and interpret expressions of facts, knowledge, requirements and other information.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] Gellish can be used in combination with SQL, RDF/XML, OWL and various other meta-languages.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] The Gellish standard is a combination of ISO 10303-221 (AP221) and ISO 15926.
[src:json-schema/data-exchange] The following describes and compares popular data exchange languages.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:json-schema/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:json-schema/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:json-schema/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:json-schema/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:json-schema/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:json-schema/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:json-schema/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:json-schema/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:json-schema/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:json-schema/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:json-schema/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:json-schema/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:json-schema/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:json-schema/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:json-schema/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:json-schema/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:json-schema/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:json-schema/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:json-schema/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:json-schema/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:json-schema/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:json-schema/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:json-schema/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:json-schema/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:json-schema/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:json-schema/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:json-schema/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:json-schema/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:json-schema/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:json-schema/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:json-schema/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:json-schema/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:json-schema/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:json-schema/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:json-schema/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:json-schema/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:json-schema/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:json-schema/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:json-schema/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:json-schema/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:json-schema/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:json-schema/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:json-schema/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:json-schema/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:json-schema/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:json-schema/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:json-schema/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:json-schema/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:json-schema/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:json-schema/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:json-schema/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:json-schema/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:json-schema/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:json-schema/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:json-schema/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:json-schema/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:json-schema/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:json-schema/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:json-schema/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:json-schema/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:json-schema/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:json-schema/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:json-schema/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:json-schema/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:json-schema/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:json-schema/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:json-schema/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:json-schema/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:json-schema/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:json-schema/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:json-schema/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:json-schema/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:json-schema/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:json-schema/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:json-schema/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:json-schema/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:json-schema/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:json-schema/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:json-schema/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:json-schema/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:json-schema/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:json-schema/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:json-schema/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:json-schema/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:json-schema/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:json-schema/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:json-schema/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:json-schema/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:json-schema/reference-type] The JSON Schema Office Hours Now Runs Weekly!
[src:json-schema/reference-type] The `type` keyword is fundamental to JSON Schema because it specifies the data type that a schema should expect.
[src:json-schema/reference-type] These types have analogs in most programming languages, though they may go by different names.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:json-schema/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:json-schema/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:json-schema/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:json-schema/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:json-schema/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:json-schema/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:json-schema/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:json-schema/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:json-schema/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:json-schema/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:json-schema/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:json-schema/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:json-schema/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:json-schema/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:json-schema/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:json-schema/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:json-schema/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:json-schema/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:json-schema/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:json-schema/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:json-schema/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:json-schema/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:json-schema/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:json-schema/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:json-schema/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:json-schema/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:json-schema/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:json-schema/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:json-schema/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:json-schema/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:json-schema/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:json-schema/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:json-schema/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:json-schema/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:json-schema/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:json-schema/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:json-schema/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:json-schema/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:json-schema/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:json-schema/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:json-schema/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:json-schema/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:json-schema/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:json-schema/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:json-schema/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:json-schema/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:json-schema/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:json-schema/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:json-schema/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:json-schema/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:json-schema/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:json-schema/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:json-schema/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:json-schema/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:json-schema/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:json-schema/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
